## [2026-05-13] PATTERN: bare Bash in settings.json = shell-wide wildcard
**Project:** global | **Type:** pattern | **Importance:** 2
**Tags:** claude-code, permissions, security, settings-json, article-028

A bare tool name in Claude Code `settings.json` allow list (e.g., `"Bash"` with no argument pattern) is equivalent to a shell-wide wildcard — auto-approves every invocation regardless of content. With `skipAutoPermissionPrompt: true` set, this means zero user gates on any shell command. Fix: replace with specific tool-pattern rules like `"Bash(git *)"`, `"Bash(kubectl *)"`, etc. The `broad_wildcard_rules` metric in the Article 023 baseline does NOT distinguish shell-wide grants from tool-specific wildcards — add `shell_wide_bash_grants` as a separate metric. Commands not in the allow list (curl, docker, make, cat, ls) will now prompt for approval.

---

## [2026-05-13] PATTERN: CLAUDE.md token budget management via ~/docs/ extraction
**Project:** global | **Type:** pattern | **Importance:** 2
**Tags:** claude-md, token-budget, article-028, context-optimization

Estimate tokens as `ceil(words / 0.75)`. Single-file threshold: 2500 tokens. When over budget, extract the two largest sections to `~/docs/<name>.md` reference files, replace inline with a 1-line pointer, and add pointers to the Reference section. Keep in-context: tier tables, core trigger lists, short behavioral rules. Move to docs/: verbose A1–A5 lists, briefing formats, multi-line protocol detail, deployment-specific patterns (e.g., Chainguard). After extraction, CLAUDE.md went 2910→2498 tokens with all rules preserved.

---

## [2026-05-13] PATTERN: staged remediation workflow (Article 028 two-prompt)
**Project:** global | **Type:** pattern | **Importance:** 1
**Tags:** article-028, remediation, workflow, staged-changes

Prompt 1: read-only audit → ranked findings table at `$SCRATCH/00-FINDINGS.md` (score = blast_radius × ease_of_fix). Prompt 2: stage fix in scratch only — never touch live files until human reviews diff. Artifacts: timestamped backup with byte-count verification, proposed replacement, unified diff patch, executable `14-undo.sh` (single `cp` restore). Human applies with one `cp` command. Scratch at `~/.claude/experiments/YYYY-MM-DD-028-anti-patterns/`. Use subdirs (A1/, A4/) when remediating multiple findings in same session.

